before_election = [[Pinarayi Vijayan]]\n| before_party = Communist Party of India (Marxist) \n| after_election = [[Pinarayi Vijayan]]\n| after_party = Communist Party of India (Marxist)\n}}\nIn 2019, six assembly by-elections were held to the [[Kerala Niyamasabha]] on 23 September and 21 October, which consists of 140 constituencies in total. \n\nBy-election took place in two phases. The first phase was conducted on 23 September for [[Pala (State Assembly constituency)|Pala Constituency]].<ref>{{cite web \n | url     = https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/pala-bypoll-on-september-23/articleshow/70833494.cms\n | website = timesofindia.indiatimes.com\n | title   = Pala Bypoll on September 23, Times of India\n}}</ref> \nThe remaining 5 assembly constituencies ([[Manjeshwaram (State Assembly constituency)|Manjeshwaram]], [[Ernakulam (State assembly constituency)|Ernakulam]], [[Aroor (State Assembly constituency)|Aroor]], [[Konni (State Assembly constituency)|Konni]] and [[Vattiyoorkavu (State Assembly constituency)|Vattiyoorkavu]]) voted to elect their representatives on 21 October.<ref>{{cite web \n | url     =  https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/story/bypolls-to-five-kerala-seats-on-october-21-1601648-2019-09-21 \n | website = www.indiatoday.in\n | title   = Bypolls to five Kerala seats on October 21, India Today\n}}</ref>\nThe counting of votes was conducted on 27 September (Pala) and on 24 October (the other five constituencies).\n\n==Schedule for the by-elections==\n===Pala===\nThe first phase by-election was held for the [[Pala (State Assembly constituency)|Pala Constituency]] in Kerala.<ref>{{cite web\n | url     = http://www.ceo.kerala.gov.in/byeElection093Schedule2019.html\n | website = www.ceo.kerala.gov.in\n | title   = Schedule for Kerala Assembly Byelections 2019 (Phase-1)\n}}</ref> \n{|border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | By-Election Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Day\n|----\n|Election Declaration\n|25/08/2019 \n|Sunday\n|----\n|Issue of Gazette Notification\n|28/08/2019\n|Wednesday\n|----\n|Last date of filing Nomination\n|04/09/2019\n|Wednesday\n|----\n|Scrutiny of Nominations\n|05/09/2019\n|Thursday\n|----\n|Last date of withdrawal of candidatures\n|07/09/2019\n|Saturday\n|----\n|Polling \n|23/09/2019\n|Monday\n|----\n|'''Counting of votes'''\n|'''27/09/2019'''\n|'''Friday'''\n|}\n\n===Manjeshwaram, Ernakulam, Aroor, Konni and Vattiyoorkavu===\nThe second phase by-elections were held for the remaining '''5''' vacant assembly constituencies in Kerala.<ref>{{cite web\n | url     = http://www.ceo.kerala.gov.in/byeElectionScheduleOct2019.html\n | website = www.ceo.kerala.gov.in\n | title   = Schedule for Kerala Assembly Byelections 2019 (Phase-2)\n}}</ref> \n{|border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | By-Election Event\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Day\n|----\n| Election Declaration\n| 21/09/2019\n| Saturday\n|----\n| Issue of Gazette Notification\n| 23/09/2019\n| Monday\n|----\n| Last date of filing Nomination\n| 30/09/2019\n| Monday\n|----\n| Scrutiny of Nominations\n| 01/10/2019\n| Tuesday\n|----\n| Last date of withdrawal of candidatures\n| 03/10/2019\n| Thursday\n|----\n| Polling \n| 21/10/2019\n| Monday\n|----\n| '''Counting of votes'''\n| '''24/10/2019'''\n| '''Thursday'''\n|}\n\n== Electorates ==\nThere were 11,36,616 electorates from the six Niyamasabha constituencies where the by-elections were held. Constituencywise details are given below:\n\n{|border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Number\n! scope=\"col\" | Constituency\n! scope=\"col\" | Electorates\n|----\n|1\n|[[Manjeshwaram (State Assembly constituency)|Manjeshwaram]]\n|2,14,779\n|----\n|82\n|[[Ernakulam (State assembly constituency)|Ernakulam]]\n|1,55,306\n|----\n|93\n|[[Pala (State Assembly constituency)|Pala]]\n|1,79,107\n|----\n|102\n|[[Aroor (State Assembly constituency)|Aroor]]\n|1,91,898\n|----\n|114\n|[[Konni (State Assembly constituency)|Konni]]\n|1,97,956\n|----\n|133\n|[[Vattiyoorkavu (State Assembly constituency)|Vattiyoorkavu]]\n|1,97,570\n|}\n\n== Alliances and parties ==\nThere are two major political coalitions in Kerala. The [[United Democratic Front (Kerala)|United Democratic Front]] (UDF) is the coalition of centrist and center-left parties led by the [[Indian National Congress]]. The [[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|Left Democratic Front]] (LDF) is the coalition of left-wing and far-left parties, led by the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] (CPI(M)).\n\n=== {{legend2|{{Left Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}}|[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]]|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}} ===\n\nIt is a coalition of [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] political parties in the state. It is one of the two major political coalitions in Kerala, the other being the UDF each of which has been in power alternatively for the last two decades. LDF is now in power. The coalition consists of [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]], [[Communist Party of India|CPI]] and a variety of other smaller parties. LDF fielded four CPI(M) candidates, an NCP candidate and an independent to fight in the by-poll.\n\n{|class=\"sortable\" width=\"65%\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\" \n! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" | No.\n! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Party !! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Flag\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Symbol!!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Photo!!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Leader\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Seats contested\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Male\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Female\n|-\n|! style=\"text-align:center; background:{{Communist Party of India (Marxist)/meta/color}};color:white\"|'''1.'''\n| [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] || [[File:CPI-M-flag.svg|50px]] \n|[[File:Indian Election Symbol Hammer Sickle and Star.png|50px]]||[[File:Kodiyeri Balakrishnan.JPG|alt=|center|frameless|70x70px]]||[[Kodiyeri Balakrishnan]]\n|4 ([[Manjeshwaram (State Assembly constituency)|Manjeshwaram]], [[Aroor (State Assembly constituency)|Aroor]], [[Konni (State Assembly constituency)|Konni]] and [[Vattiyoorkavu (State Assembly constituency)|Vattiyoorkavu]])\n|4\n|0\n|-\n|! style=\"text-align:center; background:{{Nationalist Congress Party/meta/color}};color:white\"|'''2.'''\n| [[Nationalist Congress Party]] ||[[File:NCP-flag.svg|50px]]  \n| || ||\n|1 ([[Pala (State Assembly constituency)|Pala]])\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|! style=\"text-align:center; background:{{Left Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}};color:white\"|'''3.'''\n| [[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF Independent]] ||[[File:LDF LOGO.jpg|50px]]\n|[[File:Auto Rickshaw Election Symbol.jpg|50px]] || [[File:A.vijayaraghavan4.jpg|alt=|center|frameless|70x70px]] ||[[A. Vijayaraghavan]]\n|1 ([[Ernakulam (State assembly constituency)|Ernakulam]])\n|1\n|0\n|}\n\n=== {{legend2|{{United Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}}|[[United Democratic Front (Kerala)|UDF]]|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}} ===\n\nIt is an alliance of central-wing political parties in the state, created by the prominent  [[Indian National Congress|INC]] party leader [[K. Karunakaran]] in the 1970s. UDF fielded four INC candidates, an IUML candidate and an independent for the vacant constituencies.\n\n{|class=\"sortable\" width=\"65%\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\" \n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" | No.\n! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Party !! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Flag\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Symbol!!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Photo!!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Leader\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Seats contested\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Male\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Female\n|-\n|! style=\"text-align:center; background:{{Indian National Congress/meta/color}};color:white\"|'''1.'''\n| [[Indian National Congress]] || [[File:Flag of the Indian National Congress.svg|50px]]  ||[[File:Hand INC.svg|42x42px|alt=|center|frameless]]\n|||[[Mullappally Ramachandran]]\n|4 ([[Ernakulam (State assembly constituency)|Ernakulam]], [[Aroor (State Assembly constituency)|Aroor]], [[Konni (State Assembly constituency)|Konni]] and [[Vattiyoorkavu (State Assembly constituency)|Vattiyoorkavu]])\n|3\n|1\n|-\n|! style=\"text-align:center; background:{{Indian Union Muslim League/meta/color}};color:white\"|'''2.'''\n| [[Indian Union Muslim League]]  ||[[File:Flag of the Indian Union Muslim League.svg|50px]]\n|[[File:Indian Election Symbol Lader.png|50px]]||[[File:Sayed Hyderali Shihab Thangal BNC.jpg|alt=|center|frameless|75x75px]]||[[Sayed Hyderali Shihab Thangal]]\n|1 ([[Manjeshwaram (State Assembly constituency)|Manjeshwaram]])\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|! style=\"text-align:center; background:{{United Democratic Front (Kerala)/meta/color}};color:white\"|'''3'''.\n| [[United Democratic Front (Kerala)|UDF Independent]] || \n| || [[File:Benny Behanan BNC.jpg|alt=|center|frameless|75x75px]] || [[Benny Behanan]]\n|1 ([[Pala (State Assembly constituency)|Pala]])\n|1\n|0\n|}\n\n=== {{legend2|{{National Democratic Alliance/meta/color}}|[[National Democratic Alliance|NDA]]|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}} ===\n\nIt is a coalition of right-leaning political parties in India. NDA gave all the six seats for the BJP to contest.\n\n{|class=\"sortable\" width=\"65%\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\" \n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |No.\n! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Party !! style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Flag\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Symbol!!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Photo!!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Leader\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Seats contested\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Male\n!style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\" |Female\n|-\n|! style=\"text-align:center; background:{{Bharatiya Janata Party/meta/color}};color:white\"|'''1.''' \n| [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] || \n|||[[File:PS Sreedharan Pillai.jpg|alt=|center|frameless|75x75px]]||[[P. S. Sreedharan Pillai|P. S Sreedharan Pillai]]\n| 6 ([[Manjeshwaram (State Assembly constituency)|Manjeshwaram]], [[Ernakulam (State assembly constituency)|Ernakulam]], [[Pala (State Assembly constituency)|Pala]], [[Aroor (State Assembly constituency)|Aroor]], [[Konni (State Assembly constituency)|Konni]] and [[Vattiyoorkavu (State Assembly constituency)|Vattiyoorkavu]])\n|6\n|0\n|}\n\n== Constituency-wise Candidates ==\n\nThe [[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]] fielded four [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]] candidates, an [[Nationalist Congress Party|NCP]] candidate and an independent to win the seats. [[United Democratic Front (Kerala)|UDF]] fielded four [[Indian National Congress|INC]] candidates, an [[Indian Union Muslim League|IUML]] candidate and an independent. [[National Democratic Alliance|NDA]] also decided to show their strength in the constituencies through six [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]] candidates. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\"|No.\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\"|Constituency\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:#666666; color:white\"|Candidates\n|-\n\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF]]\n{{legend2|#FF0000|[[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]] (4)|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}} {{legend2|#007FFF|[[Nationalist Congress Party|NCP]] (1)|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n\n{{legend2|#DB0000 |[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|Independent]] (1)|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[United Democratic Front (Kerala)|UDF]]\n{{legend2|#00BFFF|[[Indian National Congress|INC]] (4)|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}} {{legend2|green|[[Indian Union Muslim League|IUML]] (1)|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}} \n\n{{legend2|#0087BD |[[United Democratic Front (Kerala)|Independent]] (1)|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[National Democratic Alliance|NDA]]\n{{legend2|#FF9933|[[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]] (6)|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n|-\n!1\n![[Manjeshwaram (State Assembly constituency)|Manjeshwaram]]\n| M. Shankara Rai \n|{{legend2|#FF0000|[[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]]|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| [[M. C. Kamaruddin]]\n|{{legend2|green|[[Indian Union Muslim League|IUML]]|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| Raveesh Thanthri Kuntar\n|{{legend2|#FF9933|[[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]]|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n|-\n!2\n![[Ernakulam (State assembly constituency)|Ernakulam]]\n| Manu Roy\n|{{legend2|#DB0000|[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|Independent]]|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| [[T. J. Vinod]]\n|{{legend2|#00BFFF|[[Indian National Congress|INC]]|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n| C. G. Rajagopal \